commit.message: Bumped version for bugfix release.

do not wipe CFLAGS in configure.ac

When extra CFLAGS are passed in the environment for ./configure, these
are expected to be used while compiling. By setting `CFLAGS=` to an
empty value in configure.ac, distribution specific CLFAGS will not be
available anymore.

This caused linking issues on Fedora as it tries to compile with extra
hardening flags.

Signed-off-by: Niels de Vos <ndevos@redhat.com>

fix compile error with gcc-9.2.1

Fedora Rawhide (upcoming Fedora 33) has gcc-9.2.1 which causes compiling
archivemount to fail with the following error:

    archivemount.c: In function ‘getLine’:
    archivemount.c:2817:4: error: case label does not reduce to an integer constant
     2817 |    case delim: (*lineptr)[count++] = c;    /* fall through */
          |    ^~~~

The 'delim' integer constant for the switch statement should be a
compile time constant, so either hard-coded or #define'd.

Signed-off-by: Niels de Vos <ndevos@redhat.com>
Bumped version to 0.9.0 for new release.

Get archive_format of original archive properly in save function

In save(), the archive_format of oldarc was fetched before any calls to
archive_read_next_header have been made. According to the libarchive
documentation, the format is determined by reading the archive headers.
The new code calls archive_read_next_header once and then archive_format.

Use the archive_write_set_format function so that the exact format
type of the original is preserved when saving the new archive.

Fixes cybernoid/archivemount#10.
Log archive format type and filter (compression) type
Fix compiler warnings
Remove execute permission from C source file

Add AM_PROG_CC_C_O macro to configure.ac

This macro checks that the C compiler supports the -c and -o
options together, which is needed to run autoreconf -i on a git clone.

This macro is needed only for automake <1.14, but add it for
compatibility with older environments, such as CentOS 7.

commit.message: Prompt for a passphrase with -o password option

archivemount: Use constant to save block size

Remove magic numbers in archivemount.c. Adding a new constant will also
allow the user to modify the block size only once in the code if it is
required.

- Modified getattr again and set nlink to 1 for non-directories. Now
files on Samba shares can be opened.

- Modified getattr function to return a hardlink count of at least 2 for
directories. This will make them show up as directories when shared via
Samba as well.
Fixed small typo in manpage

- changed naming scheme of temporary files to avoid running
  into too long names for the filesystem in /tmp
- fixed renaming a newly created file (it got saved under its
  original name)
- activated code for creating symlinks; in old versions, symlinks
  were not saved, presumably due to a bug in libarchive, but it
  seems to work now.
- use shorter temporary file names to avoid running into OS limits
- fixed renaming of files, it got broken during last bugfix
- fixed renaming of directories
- fixed bug in insertion when subdir has same name as parent
- git ignore all archivemount-*.tgz's
- fixed moving a new file over an existing one
- corrected several parentheses in if-statements
- contributor KAICHO fixed an ifdef
- adaptions for CentOS, RHEL and Scientific Linux by contributor KAICHO

- fixed stat'ing of hardlinks in ar_readdir
- contributions by Alain Parmentier:
  * FormatRaw optimization
  * bugfix : use of off_t to support 64bits

- added readonly support for FormatRaw format
- fixed bug that mounted the fuse even when building tree failed
